On 14 April 2020, people, including MPs from European Solidarity, protested outside the State Bureau of Investigations in Kyiv in support of a Maidan activist and former Parliamentary deputy Tetiana Chornovol. The SBI opened a case against her accusing her of murder as the result of her setting fire to the office of the Party of Regions during the Maidan protests in 2014. The activists insist that arson of the office of the ruling party helped save lives of the protesters who were under fire by the police. [size=no report]

On 19 March 2020, about a dozen people blocked a trolleybus in Podilskyi district of Kiev demanding that it carries more passengers. In another part of Kyiv, people attempted to storm a bus and blocked its movement for the same reason. Due to the coronavirus COVID-19 outbreak, the number of allowed passengers in public transportation was limited to 10. [size=at least a dozen]

On 19 March 2020, people repeatedly blocked roads for minibuses and other public transportation in Odessa in demonstration against the measures to counter the spread of coronavirus COVID-19 that limit the number of allowed passengers. In one case, the demonstrators broke a tram window, while in another, they broke into a closed tram carriage and threatened the driver with a knife. [size=no report]

notes: On 27 February 2020, entrepreneurs demonstrated in Kharkiv against the construction of a road through the local market. A clash broke out between the demonstrators and utility workers who came with representatives of the local government to dismantle a fence that the demonstrators put up. About 100 people were involved in the fight. Some people suffered burns to their eyes and limbs due to the use of tear gas and a stun grenade. 53 people were arrested. [size=about 100]

source: Novoye Vremya Ukraine; Interfax; Novyny; Segodnya; Reporter-ua
notes: On 27 February 2020, about 30 masked people, including members of National Militia and Edelweiss, burst into the city council building in Zhmerynka, Vinnytsia, and tried to prevent the holding of the regular session. They threw stones and smoke bombs, damaged the front door and furniture in the room, smashed windows and clashed with the police. 10 police officers were injured. The police arrested 19 people. The reason for the attack is allegedly related to the city council's consideration to deprive the deputy mayor of authority and was supposedly organized by his opponents. [size=about 30]

assoc_actor_2: Government of Ukraine (2019-); Servant of the People
notes: On 17 February, an explosive device went off at the door of a patients' rights NGO in Podilskyi district of Kyiv. The perpetrators left a placard with a message blaming a Servant of the People deputy for a law that allows teenagers aged 14 and older to sign declarations with family doctors and visit other medical specialists without their guardians. Several news media outlets reported last week that the law allegedly allows teenagers to change their sex, transplant organs and have an abortion without parents' permission. No injuries were reported due to the explosion.
